            Title = "Purchase Orders Overview",
            Slug = "purchase-orders-overview",
            Summary = "What purchase orders are, the PO lifecycle from draft to close, line items, receiving workflow, blanket POs, and how POs connect to vendors, inventory, and jobs.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","procurement","receiving","vendors"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Purchase Orders Overview\n\nThe Purchase Orders module manages your procurement workflow — from requesting materials to receiving them on your dock. Every purchase order (PO) tracks what you ordered, from which vendor, how much you paid, and what has arrived so far.\n\n### What Is a Purchase Order?\n\nA purchase order is a formal document sent to a vendor authorizing them to supply specific parts at agreed prices. Each PO contains:\n- **Header** — vendor, optional linked job, expected delivery date, notes\n- **Line items** — one or more parts with ordered quantity and unit price\n- **Receiving records** — what has actually arrived against each line\n\n### PO Lifecycle\n\nEvery purchase order moves through a defined status workflow:\n\n1. **Draft** — PO is being prepared. Lines can be added, edited, or removed. The PO has not been sent to the vendor yet.\n2. **Submitted** — PO has been sent to the vendor. You are waiting for their acknowledgment.\n3. **Acknowledged** — The vendor has confirmed the order. You can now begin receiving items.\n4. **Partially Received** — Some line items have been received, but not all. The system tracks received vs. remaining quantities per line.\n5. **Received** — All line items are fully received. The PO is complete.\n6. **Closed** — The PO has been formally closed after receiving is complete. No further receiving is possible.\n7. **Cancelled** — The PO was cancelled before completion. Only Draft, Submitted, and Acknowledged POs can be cancelled.\n\n### Line Items\n\nEach line item on a PO represents a specific part you are ordering:\n- **Part** — selected from your Parts Catalog (assemblies are excluded)\n- **Ordered Quantity** — how many units you need\n- **Unit Price** — cost per unit (auto-fills from the part's default price if available)\n- **Line Total** — automatically calculated as quantity times unit price\n- **Received Quantity** — updated as items arrive\n- **Remaining Quantity** — ordered minus received, calculated automatically\n\nThe PO total is the sum of all line totals.\n\n### Receiving Workflow\n\nWhen materials arrive, open Receive Items from the order:\n1. It lists every line that still has items to come\n2. Enter how many units arrived for each line (or click Receive All to fill in what's left)\n3. Save to record it\n\nReceiving updates the line's received quantity and may change the PO status:\n- If some lines still have remaining quantity → **Partially Received**\n- If all lines are fully received → **Received**\n\nEach receiving event creates a receiving record with the quantity, who received it, and optional notes.\n\n### Blanket Purchase Orders\n\nA blanket PO is a long-term agreement with a vendor for a total quantity at an agreed unit price. Instead of ordering everything at once, you create releases against the blanket PO over time:\n- **Blanket Total Quantity** — the total committed quantity\n- **Agreed Unit Price** — the negotiated price per unit\n- **Blanket Expiration Date** — when the agreement expires\n- **Releases** — individual delivery requests drawn against the blanket quantity\n\nEach release specifies a line item, quantity, and requested delivery date. Releases have their own status tracking (Open, Sent, Partial Received, Received, Cancelled).\n\n### How POs Connect to Other Features\n\n**Vendors:** Every PO is linked to a vendor. You pick the vendor from your Vendors when building the order. Clicking the vendor name on the order opens the vendor's record.\n\n**Jobs:** A PO can optionally be linked to a specific job (e.g., ordering materials for a production run). The job link appears in the PO detail and list table.\n\n**Parts Catalog:** PO line items reference parts from your Parts Catalog. When selecting a part, the unit price auto-fills from the part's default price if one exists.\n\n**Inventory:** Receiving items against a PO can update inventory quantities when a storage location is specified on the receiving record.\n\n**Kanban Board:** When a job on the kanban board reaches the 'Materials Ordered' stage, the associated PO tracks what was ordered and when it arrives.\n\n### When to Use Purchase Orders\n\n- When ordering raw materials, components, or supplies from a vendor\n- When you need to track what has been ordered vs. what has arrived\n- When linking material purchases to specific jobs for cost tracking\n- When setting up blanket agreements for recurring material needs\n- When you need a paper trail for procurement (PDF export available)","sections":[]}"""
        });

