            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## When a Line Comes in Off Your Agreed Price\n\nAs you build an order, each line's price is compared against what you've agreed to pay that vendor at that quantity. If a line is off by more than a little, you get one heads-up covering the whole order (not a separate one for every line) when you go to submit. It lists each off-price line — the part, the agreed price (or 'no agreed price' when you've never set one), the price you typed, and how far off it is. For each line you decide:\n\n- **Record as an exception (the default)** — buy at the price you entered this one time. Your standing agreed price is left alone. This is the default on purpose, so a one-off doesn't quietly rewrite the price you'll pay next time.\n- **Update the agreed price** — treat the price you entered as the new going rate for that vendor and quantity, starting today. Your next orders start from the new figure.\n\nAt the bottom, **Cancel** takes you back to the order to fix a typo, and **Continue** applies your choices and submits. A quick rule of thumb: a temporary surcharge or a rush-order premium is an **exception**; a real, lasting price change from the vendor is an **update**.\n\n## Who Can Change a Filled-In Price, and Why It Asks for a Reason\n\nWhen you pick a part, its unit price fills in from your agreed price. Overwriting that filled-in price is deliberately gated:\n\n- **Who can change it** — only Admins and Managers. For anyone else the price springs back to the agreed figure with a note that they don't have permission. This keeps the floor from accidentally re-pricing a PO.\n- **Why it asks for a reason** — if you're allowed to change it, you have to say why before it sticks. Leave the reason blank and the price springs back; give a reason and it saves with the line.\n\nThe reason rides along with the order, so when purchasing or AP reviews it later they can see exactly why the price moved — no guessing. (Typing a price on a brand-new line you built from scratch, or nudging a figure that didn't come from your agreed pricing, doesn't ask for a reason.)\n\n## Getting a Second Opinion on a Price\n\nIf your install has the assistant turned on, you can ask for a quick review of a price you're about to override. You'll get a short read on how far the price sits from what you've agreed to — flagged low, medium, or high depending on how big the gap is — plus a sentence or two of plain-language justification you can drop straight into the reason box. Treat it as a sanity check on whether a jump is worth questioning with the vendor, not as an approval.\n\n## The Scannable Order Label at Receiving\n\nEach order can print a label with a scannable code. Print it and stick it on the paperwork or the staging area for an incoming shipment; when the goods land, scanning the label opens that exact order so you can go straight to Receive Items. It saves hunting for the PO number by hand on a busy dock.\n\n## Seeing What's Due to Arrive\n\nYour expected delivery dates show up on the shared calendar, so you and the receiving crew can see at a glance what's landing and when — handy for staffing the dock and chasing anything that's slipping. Your install can also share these dates out to an outside calendar app so they sit alongside the rest of your schedule.\n\n## You Won't Lose a Half-Built Order\n\nWhile you're entering lines on a new or edited order, your progress is kept for you. If you get pulled away, sign out, or come back later, the in-progress order is still there waiting — so a long line-entry session isn't lost to an interruption. It clears once you save or discard the order. It's a safety net for entering lines, not a substitute for actually saving the order when you're done.","sections":[]}"""
